Abstract = {{As DNA sequencing and synthesis become cheaper and more easily
   accessible, the scale and complexity of biological engineering projects
   is set to grow. Yet, although there is an accelerating convergence
   between biotechnology and digital technology, a deficit in software and
   laboratory techniques diminishes the ability to make biotechnology more
   agile, reproducible, and transparent while, at the same time, limiting
   the security and safety of synthetic biology constructs. To partially
   address some of these problems, this paper presents an approach for
   physically linking engineered cells to their digital footprint-we called
   it digital twinning. This enables the tracking of the entire engineering
   history of a cell line in a specialized version control system for
   collaborative strain engineering via simple barcoding protocols.}},
